article.headline: Rookie leads Mystics past Shock
article.linkText: Shock slump continues as Laimbeer awaits word
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Bill Laimbeer is hoping to become the next coach of the New York Knicks.

Until then, though, he'd like to figure out what's wrong with his current squad.

Friday, rookie Temeka Johnson scored 15 points and DeLisha Milton-Jones added 13 for the Washington Mystics as they defeated Laimbeer's slumping Detroit Shock 69-55.

"There are moments where we don't show up to play basketball, and this was one of them," he said after his team dropped to 5-5 despite a 4-0 start. "We haven't been able to find the button that will motivate them. They are just playing to play, and that's unacceptable."

With Olympian Swin Cash yet to see action this season due to a knee injury, Laimbeer went with a big starting lineup, inserting 6-foot-6 rookie Kara Braxton for small forward Ayana Walker. Braxton, though, was 0-for-5 with no rebounds in 10 minutes.

"Kara didn't show," Laimbeer said.

Braxton, making her first career start, couldn't explain what happened.

"I don't know what is going on with us," she said. "We work so hard in practice, and then it doesn't come over into the games. It's very frustrating."

The Mystics (6-6) won their third in a row and ended a three-game road losing streak.

"This gives us a boost," Johnson said. "We're happy to be back at .500. We'll take this step forward and see what happens from here on out."

Chasity Melvin scored 12 points and Coco Miller 10 for Washington, while Charlotte Smith-Taylor added nine.

"We're feeling pretty good about ourselves right now," Washington coach Richie Adubato said. "We're not where we want to be, but we're certainly getting there."

Deanna Nolan led all scorers with 16 points, but no other Detroit player reached double figures.

"I don't know what to say," said Cheryl Ford, who finished with eight points and five rebounds. "We play 10 times harder than this in practice. I know we all want to win, but if you can't score, you can't win."

Detroit trailed by as many as 17 in the first half and still trailed 39-28 at the intermission. Washington forced eight turnovers and blocked two shots in the half.

The Mystics missed eight of their first 10 shots in the second half, but Detroit wasn't able to get closer than five points.

Chandi Jones' 3-pointer made it 52-48, but two Washington baskets moved the advantage back to eight with five minutes to go and Detroit never seriously threatened again.

Laimbeer said before the game that he remains interested in the Knicks' job, and has talked to team president and former Pistons teammate Isiah Thomas since interviewing for the job twice, but has no idea when Thomas plans to make a decision.

"I worry about it being a distraction, but I don't think it is," Laimbeer said. "I've kept the ladies informed at all times, and they support me if I get a chance to coach in the men's league."
